<subSubSection id="C373656FFFD1C8083EEEE7DC6E98990F" pageId="5" pageNumber="558" type="nomenclature">
<paragraph id="8BD636E4FFD1C8083EEEE7DC6F3398EF" blockId="5.[174,586,175,202]" box="[174,586,175,202]" pageId="5" pageNumber="558">
<heading id="D09E8188FFD1C8083EEEE7DC6F3398EF" box="[174,586,175,202]" fontSize="36" level="2" pageId="5" pageNumber="558" reason="3">
<taxonomicName id="4C694D67FFD1C8083EEEE7DC6F3398EF" authority="(Linnaeus, 1758)" baseAuthorityName="Linnaeus" baseAuthorityYear="1758" box="[174,586,175,202]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Euclidia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="558" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="glyphica">
<emphasis id="B91DEAF6FFD1C8083EEEE7DC6C0798EF" bold="true" box="[174,382,175,202]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="558">Euclidia glyphica</emphasis>
(Linnaeus, 1758)
</taxonomicName>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BD636E4FFD1C8083EA3E7836E98990F" blockId="5.[174,1233,239,490]" pageId="5" pageNumber="558">
D e s c r i p t i o n. Egg subspherical (
<figureCitation id="13522A61FFD1C8083C3AE79C6FBC992F" box="[634,709,239,266]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="4.[166,199,1717,1739]" captionTargetBox="[166,1223,174,1669]" captionTargetId="figure-13@4.[166,1224,174,1670]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Fig. 13–18. Eggs of Erebidae: Phytometrinae: 13–15 — Colobochyla salicalis; Catocalinae: 16–18 — Euclidia glyphica. Scale bars: 13, 16 — 100 µm; 14, 15, 17, 18 — 10 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6453442" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6453442/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="558">fig. 16</figureCitation>
), diameter 
<quantity id="4C919B01FFD1C8083D08E79C6EAD992F" box="[840,980,239,266]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="8.5" metricValueMax="9.0" metricValueMin="8.0" pageId="5" pageNumber="558" unit="mm" value="0.85" valueMax="0.9" valueMin="0.8">0.8–0.9 mm</quantity>
(n = 2). According to 
<bibRefCitation id="EFF84B15FFD1C8083EEEE67C6C2F990F" author="Doring, E." box="[174,342,271,298]" pageId="5" pageNumber="558" refId="ref3049" refString="Doring, E. Zur Morphologie der Schmetterlingseier. - Berlin: Akademie-Verlag, 1955. - 154 S." type="book" year="1955">Döring (1955)</bibRefCitation>
egg green colour. As egg develops, it becomes ash grey.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C373656FFFD1C8083EA3E65C69E399CF" pageId="5" pageNumber="558" type="description">
<paragraph id="8BD636E4FFD1C8083EA3E65C69E399CF" blockId="5.[174,1233,239,490]" pageId="5" pageNumber="558">
Chorion ridged, marked on two thirds surface (
<figureCitation id="13522A61FFD1C8083D59E65C6E1F996F" box="[793,870,303,330]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="4.[166,199,1717,1739]" captionTargetBox="[166,1223,174,1669]" captionTargetId="figure-13@4.[166,1224,174,1670]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Fig. 13–18. Eggs of Erebidae: Phytometrinae: 13–15 — Colobochyla salicalis; Catocalinae: 16–18 — Euclidia glyphica. Scale bars: 13, 16 — 100 µm; 14, 15, 17, 18 — 10 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6453442" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6453442/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="558">fig. 18</figureCitation>
). Rosette with 10–11 long and narrow petalled cells and 6–7 micropylar openings. The clear transition between cells of micropylar area and remaining egg surface absent (
<figureCitation id="13522A61FFD1C8083D4EE61C6E2299AF" box="[782,859,367,394]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="4.[166,199,1717,1739]" captionTargetBox="[166,1223,174,1669]" captionTargetId="figure-13@4.[166,1224,174,1670]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Fig. 13–18. Eggs of Erebidae: Phytometrinae: 13–15 — Colobochyla salicalis; Catocalinae: 16–18 — Euclidia glyphica. Scale bars: 13, 16 — 100 µm; 14, 15, 17, 18 — 10 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6453442" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6453442/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="558">fig. 17</figureCitation>
). There are 28–32 slightly wavy longitudinal ridges (
<bibRefCitation id="EFF84B15FFD1C8083FDAE6FC6F42998F" author="Doring, E." box="[410,571,399,426]" pageId="5" pageNumber="558" refId="ref3049" refString="Doring, E. Zur Morphologie der Schmetterlingseier. - Berlin: Akademie-Verlag, 1955. - 154 S." type="book" year="1955">Döring, 1955</bibRefCitation>
). Transverse walls narrow and distinct as ridges. Columnar cells broad and short (
<figureCitation id="13522A61FFD1C8083F9EE6DC6F5399EF" box="[478,554,431,458]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="6.[166,199,1722,1744]" captionTargetBox="[166,1224,174,1671]" captionTargetId="figure-13@6.[166,1225,174,1672]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="Fig. 19–24. Eggs of Erebidae, Catocalinae: 19, 20 — Euclidia glyphica; 21–24 — Dysgonia algira. Scale bars: 19, 22–24 — 10 µm; 20 — 1 µm; 21 — 100 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6453444" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6453444/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="558">fig. 19</figureCitation>
). Along all surface of longitudinal ridges clearly expressed aeropyles at walls junctions. The entire surface of small, densely placed fibers (
<figureCitation id="13522A61FFD1C8083A00E6BC69F599CF" box="[1088,1164,463,490]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="6.[166,199,1722,1744]" captionTargetBox="[166,1224,174,1671]" captionTargetId="figure-13@6.[166,1225,174,1672]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="Fig. 19–24. Eggs of Erebidae, Catocalinae: 19, 20 — Euclidia glyphica; 21–24 — Dysgonia algira. Scale bars: 19, 22–24 — 10 µm; 20 — 1 µm; 21 — 100 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6453444" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6453444/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="558">fig. 20</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
